  "doc_id": "43218",
  "text": "In conclusion, the percentage abundance of other glycoforms detected by MALDI-TOF MS indicates that it is likely that the microheterogeneity of the hCG␤ N-linked carbohydrates found by Elliott et al. [CITATION_1] is conserved in hCG ␤-core fragments from all normal and aberrant pregnancies. Although not precisely defining hCG␤cf glycosylation, the MALDI-TOF mass spectrum of DTTreduced hCG␤cf produces what appears to be a distinctive \"fingerprint\". For example, peaks of higher mass attributable to the increased triantennary sugar content of hCG␤cf would be expected to increase in area in the spectra of hCG ␤-core fragments from individuals with abnormal or Down syndrome pregnancies and choriocarcinoma. Until now, definitive testing for hyperglycosylation in hCG in patient urine has required multiple precipitation and chromatographic steps (31 ) followed by thiol reduction, glycan release, and HPLC [CITATION_2] . This is an approach that may be considered too time-consuming for routine clinical biochemistry. Although an extract of hCG␤cf was analyzed in our current investigation, MALDI-TOF MS analysis of unextracted urine samples from pregnant women shows a broad peak corresponding to protonated hCG␤cf, indicating that its concentration in pregnancy urine is sufficiently high for detection purposes. Further study will help to elucidate whether the reductive technique described here can be applied to pregnancy or choriocarcinoma urine, possibly after desalting and concentration by centrifugal ultrafiltration [CITATION_3] . The potential clinical utility for distinguishing between normal pregnancy and Down syndrome pregnancy by this approach needs to be demonstrated and is currently under investigation.",
